<TEXT>
when a municipal office building goes up 
across the road from the town common it will be a monument to the 
drawing power of bake sales bottle drives and fourth of july 
chicken barbecues 
along with car and quilt raffles turkey suppers lobster bakes 
fall foliage festivals boat trips and dinner theaters not to 
mention a hawaiian pig roast a jazz concert and a white elephant 
sale 
plus letters and doortodoor solicitations that brought in 
contributions from 648 people 
instead of having taxpayers shell out an average of 15 for each 
of the next 20 years a civic group has staged dozens of 
fundraisers to come up with the 250000 to buy a site for the 
building and then donate it to the town 
its like a dream said henry rowe one of the founders of 
the boothbay civic association and its president now only 40000 
away from its goal the nonprofit association expects to complete 
its campaign this fall 
the level of commitment is amazing said town manager 
victoria dyer 
the association formed after the town initially decided to build 
the new town offices now situated up a steep flight of stairs over 
the town garage at a ball field half a mile down a side road 
association members decided to buy the property in the center of 
town that now holds an abandoned garage and turn what many 
consider an eyesore into a landmark 
the central location is at a crossroads the gateway to boothbay 
harbor and other villages along a scenic peninsula where thousands 
of visitors stream in and out on summer days 
the association answered protests the site would be too costly 
by raising the money on its own the town will pay for construction 
of the building 
i think that every community in the country ought to have a 
civic association to do whats right away from the tax dollar 
said former boat builder chetley rittall regarded as the moving 
spirit behind the project 
rittall and his followers organized the association in 1987 
with the first 100 coming from a supper put on by the fire 
department within months the group had raised 50000 enough to 
secure a 200000 mortgage on the garage 
fishermen donated 1250 pounds of lobsters for two lobster 
bakes at times 100 women were enlisted to turn out pies for bake 
sales 
the project has not been without hitches association leaders 
felt badly served when the town of 3500 yearround residents sent 
a bill for 2500 for taxes on the garage property despite the 
groups nonprofit status 
although the association plans to appeal the assessment its 
leaders are amused at the irony 
if we dont pay the taxes the town will have a lien on the 
property but were going to be donating it to the town anyway 
rowe said 
