<TEXT>
beijing will evict 102000 migrant workers in the 
coming months as part of a drive to spruce up its image before it 
hosts the asian games in september an official newspaper reported 
today 
the china daily said only those migrants with special 
certificates would be allowed to stay in the capital 
the newspaper said thorough checks will be made of workplaces 
hiring rural labor and those employing unregistered laborers will 
be fined 
the report said the sweep against migrant workers would keep 
urban unemployment down and ensure a clean and secure environment 
for the asian games 
an estimated 100000 foreign athletes sports officials and 
tourists are expected in the capital for the games they will be 
the largest international sports event ever staged in china 
chinese authorities trying to improve the nations image after 
the bloody military crackdown on the prodemocracy movement last 
year are intent on making sure the games go off without a hitch 
in 1987 more than 1 million rural workers flooded beijing a 
city of 10 million to work in the construction and service 
industries and take manual labor jobs unpopular with city residents 
the peasant workers shoddily dressed and carrying all their 
belongings on their back camped out at the overcrowded railway 
station and set up makeshift stalls on city streets 
chinese are legally allowed to live and work only in places 
where they are officially registered with the government 
authorities previously did little to stop the migrants because they 
provided a needed source of unskilled labor 
the demand for the unskilled workers declined sharply in late 
1988 after the government introduced an austerity program that 
brought an abrupt end to the construction boom 
last year beijing asked 284000 migrant workers to leave the 
capital the china daily said it quoted city officials as saying 
the desirable number of rural farmers allowed to work in beijing 
should be no more than 350000 
</TEXT>
