<TEXT>
president bush is prodding israeli prime 
minister yitzhak shamir to open a dialogue with palestinian arabs 
as the first step in reviving longstalled middle east peace talks 
bush in a lengthy letter asked the prime minister what his new 
rightwing government was willing to do to promote peace and 
whether he still supports a plan for elections of palestinian 
representatives in the occupied territories officials said monday 
the presidents letter sent in the last few days adds weight 
to a warning by secretary of state james a baker iii that the 
united states will stop trying to get peace talks under way unless 
shamir makes compromises to open a dialogue with palestinians 
confirming receipt of bushs letter shamir said bush asked me 
for replies and explanations about our path in the framework of the 
peace process 
naturally we will reply to him shamir said in a televised 
interview in jerusalem we will explain to him to the best of 
our ability our attitude our proposals and i sincerely hope if 
here and there there are differences of opinion we will reach an 
agreement 
the white house did not release bushs letter but presidential 
spokesman marlin fitzwater said it congratulated shamir on forming 
a new government after a threemonth political deadlock 
the president asked him for a description of where he stands 
on the peace process at this month fitzwater said he said bush 
expressed hopes that shamir remained committed to the plan he 
espoused last year 
the united states and israel have been deeply divided over steps 
to implement shamirs plan 
last week shamirs government set restrictive new conditions on 
his proposal darkening prospects that it ever would be implemented 
baker in an appearance before a house committee last wednesday 
appeared to question whether the israeli government was genuinely 
committed to the peace process 
he said officials of shamirs new government had dismissed the 
plan for a palestinian dialogue and were adding new conditions that 
palestinians must meet as a price for talks 
now if thats going to be the approach and thats going to 
be the attitude there wont be any dialogue and there wont be any 
peace and the united states of america cant make it happen 
baker said 
he offered the white house telephone number and said in a clear 
message to israel when youre serious about peace call us 
in may 1989 shamir proposed holding elections among palestinian 
arabs who live on the west bank and gaza these palestinians would 
negotiate with israel the terms for five years of limited 
selfrule to be followed by a second round of talks on an overall 
settlement of the arabisraeli dispute 
baker concluded last fall that shamirs plan was the best 
approach to getting negotiations started he consulted over several 
months with egypt israel and through egyptian intermediaries 
with the palestine liberation organization 
a formula devised by baker to implement shamirs proposal called 
for talks between israelis and palestinians in cairo it also 
provided for the participation of palestinians expelled from the 
territories and others who had residences in east jerusalem 
shamir evidently objecting to the provisions on the 
palestinians refused to submit the plan to the israeli cabinet for 
approval 
bush meanwhile declared east jerusalem which shamir has 
vowed to retain occupied territory 
the israeli government collapsed in turmoil in march and the 
us initiative went on hold as israel struggled to form a new 
government 
david levy the foreign minister of israels new government 
charged last week that bakers proposal was out of sync with the 
plan outlined last year by shamir 
the israeli government peace initiative has been changed and 
distorted and turned into questions the baker questions to which 
israel was required to answer yes or no levy said no 
nation can be asked to gamble with its own survival 
</TEXT>
