the head of military intelligence in 
hungary says a former us military mans spying for the east bloc 
may have actually helped the cause of peace 
retired army sgt clyde lee conrad 43 was sentenced to life in 
prison this month by a west german court that found him guilty of 
passing secrets to hungary and czechoslovakia from 1975 through 
1985 in return for 12 million 
the trial judge in the case said conrad who was convicted of 
treason had endangered the entire defense capability of the 
west 
but brig gen janos kovacs who has headed hungarian military 
intelligence since october said the spying probably led to better 
eastwest ties because the information conrad produced made it 
clear nato was not planning to attack the soviet union or its 
allies 
kovacs said in an interview monday that this knowledge helped 
lead to a new approach to eastwest relations on the part of the 
warsaw pact 
the interesting paradox was that conrads information helped 
prove that there are no offensive nato plans and this led 
soberthinking people to reassess the situation and to develop a 
new approach he said 
