<TEXT>
settlement of a 123yearold dispute between 
the united states and the soviet union over the maritime boundary 
in the bering sea is unlikely to prove a bonanza to the fishermen 
and oil drillers of either nation 
neither side can say they beat anybody out of anything says 
clement tillion an alaska commercial fisherman who is chairman of 
the american section of the international north pacific fisheries 
commission its a very nice agreement 
tillion and others said that for the fishermen of both countries 
the main benefit of the agreement signed with little fanfare 
during the recent ussoviet summit here will be that they now 
know for sure where the line is supposed to be 
for oilmen the effect will be less than for fishermen there 
are lots of fish in the bering sea but nobody has yet discovered 
any oil 
the dispute arose out of the negotiations that led to the us 
purchase of alaska from russia in 1867 the argument has revolved 
around whether the negotiators used a terrestrial globe or a 
mercator projection map 
theres a 60mile difference in the middle because of the 
distortion of the mercator projection tillion said in a recent 
interview we in effect split the difference 
a state department official speaking on condition he not be 
identified said the boundary line did not become an issue until 
the 1970s when both sides claimed exclusive jurisdiction to 200 
miles offshore 
then they started bumping up against each other he said 
in the most recent of many incidents the coast guard seized a 
soviet fishing vessel on may 11 after authorities said it was 
caught with its nets in the water inside the us 200mile fishery 
limit 
now the fishermen can fish without threat of being harassed 
because of the uncertainty of the boundary line the state 
department official said 
tillion however cautioned against expecting that fishermen 
will no longer get in trouble by straying over the border 
commercial fishermen are larcenous he said 
as for oil it doesnt really make a lot of material 
difference said susan hall a spokeswoman for the minerals 
management service in the interior department we didnt lose or 
gain resourcewise by it 
the advantage of course is that it is settled ms hall 
said it does define beyond dispute a sort of western edge to our 
planning areas 
oil companies spent hundreds of millions of dollars in the early 
1980s on bering sea oil and gas exploration leases but discovered 
nothing they generally shied away from tracts inside the disputed 
area 
despite the agreement spokesman bill smith of exxon one of the 
leaders in the earlier bidding said the company had no plans at 
present for further bering sea exploration 
it is too early for us to say anything about it smith said 
we do not know what the effects will be 
the soviets conceded their rights to the united states in three 
areas within their 200mile zone and the united states made a 
similar concession regarding an area farther south within its zone 
the state department official said 
tillion said this gives the united states the right to manage 
the pollock fishery in the areas that it gains he said the soviet 
gains were smaller but on neither side did they amount to very 
much 
its almost a wash he said 
giorgi shchekochikhin a spokesman for the soviet embassy said 
the basic provisions of this treaty eliminate a problem between 
the two countries in the pacific 
in the past he said most official ussoviet dealings had 
been between the east coast of the united states and the western 
part of the soviet union 
with increasing contacts between siberia and alaska he said 
it is becoming of more major importance to have no more problems 
between our two countries at this point 
