<TEXT>
the once banned and hunted radio 
solidarity has finally taken to the airwaves legally 
on monday the radio station that operated underground for eight 
years began regular daily fm broadcasts to the warsaw region 
programming is to feature music and independent news reports 
at first the station is to broadcast 6 hours a day 
eventually it plans to have programming 20 hours a day the 
staterun pap news agency reported 
the station is a private company jointly owned by the foundation 
of radio solidarity an english company called radio trust the 
state radio committee and a british citizen ludomir lasocki all 
earnings from the station in its first three years are to be 
reinvested in the station 
the station had operated illegally from march 1982 until april 
28 1989 when it was permitted limited broadcasts on state radio 
channels as part of the agreement with thencommunist authorities 
to promote solidaritys electoral campaign 
the last such electoral broadcast was june 30 and the 
underground activists associated with radio solidarity immediately 
began planning for legal operation on a separate wavelength 
according to pap the selection of topics for broadcasts will 
depend largely on listeners with whom the station hopes to be in 
permanent contact 
radio solidarity was born four months after the december 1981 
martiallaw crackdown on solidarity it made brief clandestine 
broadcasts from time to time on various fm frequencies using hidden 
transmitters 
occasionally it would broadcast audio messages on the 
frequencies used by state television interrupting the official 
news 
it was constantly playing hideandseek with the police who 
with limited success would track the signal to seize the 
transmitters and broadcasters 
officials also learned to counter the broadcasts by jamming them 
with loud disco music 
