<TEXT>
even before he takes office presidentelect 
alberto fujimori is staking his power and prestige on a highstakes 
quest for international aid 
the political neophyte sets off this weekend for the united 
states japan and south korea on a trip that represents a dramatic 
turnabout for peru 
outgoing president alan garcia turned his back on the 
international financial community fujimori who takes office july 
28 wants to bring peru back into the fold 
the presidenttobe has a powerful motivation for his effort 
the peru he will inherit is bankrupt battered by 2000 percent 
annual inflation thousands of peruvians are on strike and four in 
five lack steady work a 10year guerrilla war has claimed more 
than 18500 lives 
if fujimori succeeds it wont be the first time hes overcome 
long odds 
his landslide win over famed novelist mario vargas llosa in the 
june 10 runoff election capped a comefrombehind campaign as 
perus 86th president he will join the small minority of 
democratically elected leaders in the countrys 169year history 
since independence 
analysts say the survival of perus latest 10yearold stint of 
democracy likely hinges on fujimori a restless military is ready 
to intervene if the government proves unable to keep peru from 
falling into chaos they say 
in washington where his 12day tour will start june 25 
fujimori is to meet officials of the international monetary fund 
the world bank and the interamerican development bank 
it may be something of a fencemending mission 
garcia upon coming to power in 1985 limited payment on the 
nations 20 billion foreign debt to 10 percent of export earnings 
shortly afterward peru stopped payment altogether 
in the first third of this year alone peru missed 16 billion 
in payments to international lending institutions the amount 
overdue to private banks is believed to be even higher 
fujimori will travel next to japan which has said it is willing 
to resume loans to peru if the country shows a willingness to deal 
with its serious social and economic problems 
fujimoris japanese ancestry has raised hopes of greater access 
to japanese aid peru was the largest recipient of japanese aid in 
latin america in cumulative terms until 1988 but dropped to 
fourthlargest after it defaulted on payments and japan cut off its 
yen credits 
one official in japans foreign ministry said peru owes japan an 
estimated 1 billion in government and private debts 
garcia contended in a recent interview that peruvian democracy 
has survived because he resisted the austerity measures recommended 
by the perus creditors but many believe perus economy cannot 
survive much longer without the drastic measures advocated by 
vargas llosa 
inflation in the first two weeks of june alone was 25 percent 
central bank reserves stand at 900 million mostly in gold and 
silver liquid reserves are 134 million enough to pay for less 
than two months of imports 
during the campaign fujimori played on worries about vargas 
llosas plans for economic shock treatment and cultivated poor 
indigenous peruvians who associated the novelist with the 
europeandescended elite 
he said the economy could recover with gradual measures but 
never fully explained what those would be 
vargas llosa planned to privatize most of the chronically 
inefficient public enterprises and cut the bloated bureaucracy 
but in a country where 40 percent of the population lives in 
extreme poverty vargas llosas proposals raised the specter of 
greater suffering fujimori was the beneficiary of those fears 
in order to get anything accomplished fujimoris government 
will have to court support from other parties but garcias 
leftleaning aprista party opposes austerity measures and fredemo 
the centerright coalition that supported vargas llosa is still 
feeling the sting of defeat 
an aprista leader speaking on condition of anonymity said he 
expects serious instability if fujimori fails to forge a broad 
consensus in six months or less 
since fujimori is a newcomer in peruvian politics he has no 
links to traditional parties and no established base of support 
but analysts say he may be able to turn that lack of political 
connections into an asset when its time to compromise a time 
that could come soon 
</TEXT>
