<TEXT>
a new infrared device that measures a cars 
exhaust from the side of the road as the vehicle drives past may 
someday replace state testing programs in which emissions are 
collected from the tailpipe of an idling auto 
in a test in illinois the device showed that 8 percent of 
chicagos autos produce about half the citys carbon monoxide 
pollution and that relatively new vehicles as well as old clunkers 
are among the worst polluters 
in nevada the environmental protection agency concluded that 
the device called feat for fuel efficiency automobile test was an 
accurate tool 
some officials believe the device invented three years ago by 
university of denver chemistry professor donald h stedman could 
streamline emissions testing and improve pollution control 
further down the road the ultimate goal is to identify 
precisely that relatively small percentage and require them to come 
in for inspection and maintenance rather than requiring everyone 
said bill denham of the illinois department of energy and natural 
resources 
in the conventional testing station the emissions are collected 
from the tailpipe 
with feat the infrared beam source and the detector are placed 
on opposite sides of a road and take their reading as the car 
passes stedman said monday a computer calculates the emissions 
and a camera snaps a picture of the license plate to determine the 
vehicles age 
he said the feat can measure 1000 cars an hour in contrast 
illinois testing stations typically check 17 vehicles per hour 
said james matheny of the illinois environmental protection 
agencys vehicle emission testing program 
marc pitchford who was in charge of testing the device for the 
epa in nevada said roadside testing would save illinois 12 
million a year on its emissions program which state officials put 
at 21 million to 23 million 
stedman said hydrocarbon pollution would be reduced by catching 
cars that pollute sooner he said many drivers tamper with their 
cars to pass annual emissions tests 
but the feat has its skeptics 
matheny said little research exists on how many sensors would be 
needed and on where to locate them for thorough testing 
and steven cadle a research scientist for general motors who 
developed a test similar to stedmans said the roadside tests 
assume an autos output remains constant 
i would not feel comfortable writing that person a ticket 
he added 
</TEXT>
