batticaloa 140 miles northeast of colombo in this indian ocean 
island nation has been a flashpoint in recent fighting in the war 
that has grown out of bitter ethnic rivalries 
troops moved in from a nearby airstrip and military camp the 
officials said speaking on condition of anonymity 
tamil rebels withdrew from the town on monday into the 
surrounding jungles to continue fighting military officials said 
law and order in the town had broken down and that looting of 
stores was widespread 
also today government forces overran tamil rebel positions in 
the east and repulsed an attack on an army garrison in the north 
officials said 
the army used helicopter gunships and repeated machinegun fire 
to stave off an early morning attack by rebels on the jaffna 
military garrison said military officials who spoke on condition 
of anonymity 
jaffna 190 miles north of colombo is headquarters to the 
liberation tigers of tamil eelam the main rebel milita 
the officials said the rebels used bulldozers and heavy 
earthmoving equipment in their bid to seize the 200yearold dutch 
fort where the garrison is located about 150 soldiers were in the 
garrison at the time they said 
in the east government police commandos overran two rebel camps 
and freed 75 people who had been held captive the officials said 
eightdayold rebel sieges of two military camps near the town of 
batticaloa were broken when army reinforcements crossed swamps and 
jungles to reach the area they said 
there were no details of casualties in the latest fighting but 
deputy defense minister ranjan wijeratne said monday that 600 
rebels had been killed since june 11 he did not speak of 
government casualties 
in addition at least 378 people are reported to have been 
killed the figure includes at least 137 unarmed policemen said to 
have been massacred by the rebels the death toll was compiled from 
reports by witnesses military officials and rebel sources 
the fighting began june 10 after tiger rebels overran police 
stations in the tamildominated northern and eastern provinces 
ending a yearlong ceasefire with security forces 
two further attempts during the week to stop the fighting broke 
down 
tamil rebels have been fighting for an independent nation since 
1983 claiming their minority community is being discriminated 
against by the sinhalese who control the army and the government 
in may 1989 the rebels agreed to a ceasefire with the 
government 
ten months later indian peacekeeping soldiers who had tried in 
vain to disarm the rebels over 32 months withdrew from sri lanka 
that left the rebels in control of most major towns in the north 
and east 
at least 11000 people including 1100 indian soldiers have 
been killed in the war 
the government and the rebels began talks on the political 
future of the regions but the talks had not made much headway 
before the fighting resumed 
tamils make up 18 percent of the islands 16 million people and 
sinhalese comprise 75 percent 
