the interior ministry today said it had arrested opposition 
figures dumitru dinca and nica leon leader of the small national 
democratic party 
the two were being held as part of an investigation into the 
53day antigovernment protest on university square that 
clubwielding riot police broke up on wednesday 
on monday authorities detained marian munteanu a student 
leader severely beaten by progovernment miners last week munteanu 
was removed from his hospital bed to an interior ministry hospital 
on charges of instigating violence 
wednesdays crackdown by police triggered rioting that ended the 
next day when coal miners called in by iliescu cleared the city 
center beating with clubs and iron bars anyone they suspected of 
being a government opponent 
the vigilantes also sacked the offices of opposition parties and 
shut down opposition newspapers 
munteanus wife claudia sought refuge at the home of dutch 
ambassador coen stork the netherlands embassy said 
she has been at the residence of the ambassador since 
yesterday evening because she fears for her safety said charge 
daffaires kaas vran spronsam by telephone 
asked how long she would be able to stay the diplomat replied 
we will not ask her to leave 
government opponents seek the ouster of iliescu and the other 
former communists who hold top posts in the national salvation 
front which took power in the december revolution and won election 
by a landslide last month 
on monday the opposition newspapers said they would resume 
publishing the opposition romania libera daily last published 
thursday and often hard to buy was not on the streets today but 
its editors said it appeared 
student activists were targeted last week by the miners in what 
was the worst street unrest since the december revolt that toppled 
dictator nicolae ceausescu six people were killed and more than 
500 injured in the violence and the government said more than 
1000 were arrested 
the interior ministry said its chief doru viorel ursu was 
holding talks with student groups but at the same time prime 
minister petre roman said government forces had the 
responsibility and obligation to crack down on dissent 
parliaments lower house on monday gave police and soldiers the 
authority to clear from university square antigovernment 
protesters who had reassembled there beginning sunday 
most dispersed monday night and the square was quiet today 
in the 377member house of deputies only 72 voted against 
mondays motion to have the forces of law and order end the 
demonstration in the square the vote split along party lines with 
the national salvation front in favor backed by splinter parties 
and the three main opposition parties abstaining or voting no 
passage was virtually certain in the senate where the front also 
holds a majority 
in a separate measure the 114 senators present monday voted for 
government and police to take immediate measures to sanction 
firmly all those who trespassed and will trespass on public 
property 
however the senate also passed a motion critical of the 
excesses that consisted of roughing up people and damaging 
political party headquarters and public institutions 
iliescus inauguration scheduled for last week was postponed 
amid the turmoil 
