federal and state officials have sued eight 
california companies on grounds that they have been polluting 
waters and damaging marine life off los angeles and long beach 
since the 1940s the government announced today 
the justice department filed the suit on behalf of the national 
oceanic and atmospheric administration the interior department and 
the state of california noaa said 
noaa said four of the companies named in the suit were montrose 
chemical corp westinghouse electric corp stauffer chemical 
corp and potlatch corp the others were not immediately identified 
the suit alleges that the companies dumped the pesticide ddt and 
polychlorinated biphenyls or pcbs into los angeles and long 
beach harbors onto the palos verdes shelf off whites point and at 
two dump sites in the san pedro channel near santa catalina island 
fish marine mammals and sea birds were injured noaa said 
the businesses could be required under federal superfund 
legislation to pay tens of millions of dollars to restore damage to 
natural resources and habitat they could also be required to 
remove or treat contaminated underwater sediments restock fish or 
install artificial reefs 
the firms were informed in january of the governments intention 
to sue a 90day extension of the time in which they could be sued 
was negotiated in march it expired today 
noaa said the los angeles county sanitation districts another 
potential defendant signed a time extension giving the government 
until next april to decide whether to sue 
noaa said its biologists have found that both commercial and 
sports fish off los angeles have high levels of ddt and pcbs 
particularly the agency said bottlenose dolphins and california 
sea lions have the highest body fat concentrations of those two 
chemicals of any marine mammal it has ever studied 
