roy mcdonald publisher of the 
chattanooga newsfree press died in his sleep early today family 
members said he was 88 
mcdonald who started the paper in 1933 as a weekly shopper 
called the chattanooga free press commonly put in eight to 
10hour days at the newsfree press even into his 80s checking 
ads news copy and story layout he had worked monday the day 
before he died 
he was known as mr roy to his staff his colleagues his 
family and to the city 
the free press went daily in 1936 and three years later 
mcdonald bought the financially troubled chattanooga news to create 
the current newspaper the paper now has a joint operating 
agreement with the chattanooga times 
mcdonald was also a major force in chattanooga business and 
civic affairs serving on the board at erlanger medical center and 
helping create blue crossblue shield of tennessee 
he was born nov 25 1901 in graysville tenn 
as a young man he managed grocery stores for his father before 
founding a grocery chain called the homes stores in 1924 the chain 
grew to more than 70 stores in the chattanooga area before he sold 
it in 1967 
the afternoon newsfree press and the morning times published 
jointly until 1966 when mcdonald began a sunday edition to compete 
with the times the times responded with an afternoon paper called 
the chattanooga post 
the newspapers sued each other and the post was discontinued in 
1970 after times officials signed a consent decree in an antitrust 
suit filed by the justice department 
the times also paid a settlement to the newsfree press that was 
reported to be 2 million to 3 million mcdonald used that money 
to buy a new press 
in 1980 the papers entered a new operating agreement in which 
the times which had lost 2 million over five years agreed to 
give up its sunday edition 
survivors include his wife elizabeth a son frank s mcdonald 
daughters helen mcdonald exum dr martha w mcdonald betsy 
mcdonald anderson and nancy mcdonald reinke and numerous 
grandchildren 
