made the deals under the departments export enhancement program 
or eep 
delivery of the wheat is scheduled for october he said 
the sales were part of 2 million tons authorized for china under 
eep on may 2 previous allocations had been exhausted except for 
5050 tons dickerson said china has 1145425 tons remaining in 
its current allocation 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat the latest sales would be about 132 million bushels at 
current prices estimated by usda at around 333 per bushel the 
wheat would have a farm value of around 44 million 
under eep arrangements private exporters can sell us 
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in 
selected overseas markets and then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies 
dickerson said the latest subsidies averaged 1662 per ton or 
about 45 cents per bushel 
