a towns ordinance strictly regulating 
signs discriminates against political speech and therefore is 
unconstitutional a superior court judge ruled this morning 
judge melanie famiglietti threw out the case against a 
barrington man who had been convicted of erecting signs in his yard 
in 1984 and 1985 without a permit as required by town ordinances 
the judge said the signs that james lemoi 70 installed in his 
yard were appeals for help after the death of his wife and a fire 
at his house and a political statement about town officials both 
of which were prohibited without a permit from the town 
barrington allows a variety of signs to be installed without a 
permit to advertise a house for sale or a professional business 
such as a law firm in a home or signs in connection with a holiday 
decoration other signs are permitted only if a permit is obtained 
before they are erected 
famiglietti said that the town cannot regulate signs by their 
content which was what it did in the case of lemoi if these 
very same signs indicated a doctors office in lemois home or 
were a theater marquee or were holiday decorations mr lemoi would 
not be in court today and would not be fined 13000 the judge 
said 
in december 1984 lemois wife died and just a few days later 
his house caught fire causing extensive damage he was not home at 
the time and was not hurt 
about 10 days after the fire lemoi put a sign up in his yard 
seeking public help seven months later after he was unable to 
obtain police or fire department reports about the fire he erected 
another sign stating simply come clean 
it was after that sign that barrington charged lemoi in district 
court with violating the town sign ordinance he was found guilty 
and fined 13000 he challenged his conviction and the american 
civil liberties unions rhode island affiliate took up the case 
when it reached superior court 
an attorney for the town michael mosco said he did not know 
whether he would appeal the ruling to the state supreme court he 
said that decision would be made by the town council 
mosco defended the ordinance saying that requiring a permit for 
certain types of signs was logical we consider any sign in the 
town of barrington as permissible he said we think its a 
reasonable sign ordinance 
