<TEXT>
the zebra mussel is one of many exotic species 
invading us waters and a broad strategy is needed to keep them 
from wreaking economic and environmental havoc experts said 
tuesday 
the river ruffe spiny water flea and tubenosed goby soon may 
become as familiar to the great lakes as the zebra mussel 
witnesses said at a hearing of the senate subcommittee on 
environmental protection 
meanwhile the asiatic clam japanese seaweed and the red tide 
are damaging shellfish and marine industries along the ocean coasts 
the newcomers threaten many native species interrupt the food 
chain and pose a danger to the us fishing industry and other 
segments of the economy said gillman d veith director of the 
environmental protection agencys office of research and 
development 
given the rate of technological change and movement of people 
it is likely that the problems resulting from invasions of 
nonnative species will increase said veith 
the city of monroe mich was forced to ration water for 
several days and spend 500000 removing zebra mussels from its 
water intake pipe last year said sen herb kohl dwis shipping 
tourism paper production and other industries could be affected if 
such problems become widespread he said 
there is growing concern that the introduction of 
nonindigenous species by ships particularly through their ballast 
water has affected the ecosystems and economies of countries 
around the world said capt thomas e thompson of the us coast 
guard 
bills pending in the house and senate would order the coast 
guard to develop and enforce regulations on dumping of ships 
ballast water the suspected source of zebra mussels which are 
native to freshwater bodies of eastern europe and the soviet union 
the tiny bivalves with zebralike stripes have spread with 
lightning speed through the great lakes since their arrival in 
1986 they fasten themselves to hard surfaces such as pipes and 
boat hulls and ingest plankton essential to the aquatic food chain 
senators from the region urged quick action and braodening the 
scopes of the bills to deal with other natural invaders 
</TEXT>
