<TEXT>
the value of us agricultural exports dropped 
slightly in april from yearearlier levels an agriculture 
department report said tuesday 
a listing of products shipped to foreign buyers showed their 
value at 335 billion down from 342 billion in april 1989 
however the cumulative value since the fiscal year began oct 1 
was up totaling 253 billion for the seven months against 246 
billion a year earlier 
the value of corn exports in april rose slightly to 5772 
million from 546 million a year ago with the soviet union the 
biggest buyer replacing japan the traditional leader 
other big corn buyers during the month were taiwan spain south 
korea and mexico 
but wheat exports dropped sharply in april to 3549 million 
from 5145 million a year earlier the soviet union remained the 
largest market followed by japan china algeria egypt taiwan 
and venezuela 
the monthly report showed soybean exports dropped to 2765 
million from 3145 million in april 1989 
shipments to the european economic community fell 
significantly accounting for most of the decline the report 
said other major markets included japan taiwan and korea 
cotton shipments in april were shown at a value of 2517 
million up from 1857 million a year earlier 
exports of livestock and livestock products in april totaled 
more than 5387 million compared with 5314 million in april 
1989 
total us agricultural exports in the current fiscal year are 
forecast at 40 billion up from 396 billion in 198889 and the 
most since they hit a record of 438 billion in 198081 
