<TEXT>
foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze blamed 
soviet officials for fueling a chemical arms buildup to win an 
honor banner of socialist competition 
the outspoken soviet diplomat said in an interview with new 
times a soviet weekly that people were correct to point out 
imbalances in the weapons stocks of east and west and that those 
responsible for soviet advantages acted irresponsibly 
those who apparently not in a struggle with imperialism but 
in a drive to win an honor banner of socialist competition poured 
barrels full of chemical poisons at a time when the world had 
stopped producing them already should be called to account 
shevardnadze said 
the edition of new times containing the interview was scheduled 
for release friday the associated press obtained an advance copy 
tuesday from soviet sources 
shevardnadzes admission that the soviet side was to blame for 
imbalances in chemical weapons stocks came a few weeks after 
president mikhail s gorbachev and president bush signed an 
agreement on the issue in washington 
the pact concluded when the us and soviet foreign ministers 
met in moscow in may requires the superpowers to destroy 80 
percent of their chemical weapons immediately they would reduce 
their stocks to 2 percent of existing levels in the next eight 
years and destroy the rest two years later if all other countries 
capable of producing chemical weapons join them in a global ban 
officials said 
the united states has an estimated 30000 tons and the soviets 
50000 tons of the weapons according to government sources and 
independent experts 
in the interview shevardnadze did not identify which soviet 
officials were responsible for the chemical weapons buildup which 
he cited as an example of overall bad policy in the arms race 
our partners act like a rational hostess who buys only as much 
food as she needs to fix a lunch when the guests leave shes not 
left with a lot to throw away we had a different psychology buy 
everything and as much as possible only to discover later a mound 
of excess he said 
