drugs to intended robbery victims and contended the matronly 
exconvict killed her victims for their social security and 
government benefit checks 
defense attorneys said the tenants who died ranging in age from 
52 to 80 and mostly poor and alcoholic did so either by natural 
causes or suicide among the victims ailments were a brain tumor 
lung disease heart disease and diabetes 
puente has pleaded innocent she could face the death penalty if 
convicted 
the judges ruling came more than seven weeks after the start of 
puentes preliminary hearing on april 27 but two of those weeks 
were spent in recess as defense lawyers prepared their case 
the hearing featured testimony by 70 prosecution witnesses and 
at least eight defense witnesses and more than 100 exhibits 
puente displayed little emotion throughout her hearing she sat 
quietly at the defense table occasionally writing notes to or 
leaning over to whisper to her attorneys 
