<TEXT>
the number of states with alternative routes 
for certifying teachers is growing but few focus on recruiting 
older educated adults with reallife experiences a study said 
tuesday 
emily feistritzer director of the national center for education 
information said a study found that most alternative teacher 
certification programs for people who have not completed a 
traditional college teacher education program are tied to teacher 
shortages 
since the shortages have not materialized as educators 
originally had predicted very few teachers are entering the 
profession through the alternate routes she said 
very few states in this nation have actually designed a 
certification path specifically to meet the demand created by the 
new and growing market of adults who already have at least a 
bachelors degree and want to teach said feistritzer 
connecticut new jersey texas arizona and arkansas are the 
best at opening their schools to such wouldbe teachers because 
job offers are available to people who have a bachelors degree in 
any subject according to the study 
however arizona accepts such teachers only at the secondary 
school level and arkansas uses them only when there are teacher 
shortages 
the united states has hired about 1 million new teachers in the 
last five years but only about 12000 have been certified through 
alternative teacher certification routes since 1985 
the center a private education research organization conducted 
a statebystate study from december 1989 to may 1990 thirtythree 
states report they are implementing alternative routes to the 
stateapproved college teacher education program for certifying 
teachers up from 23 less than two years ago eight states were 
implementing alternatives in 1983 
about a third of the states say they use alternative routes only 
if a traditionally certified teacher cannot be found the study 
said 
there is enormous variation in the alternative routes the study 
found however it said most states require a bachelors degree at 
least a cplus college grade average and passage of a basic skills 
test and sometimes a specialty area test 
the study said connecticut new jersey and texas have about the 
best statedesigned alternative programs available in all fields at 
all grade levels arizona idaho louisiana ohio and virginia 
offer programs only at the secondary level 
states that offer alternative programs only in areas of teacher 
shortages are alabama arkansas california georgia maine new 
york oregon and south carolina hawaii missouri and oklahoma 
offer alternative programs only in shortage areas at the high 
school level 
some states the study said favor emergency licensing 
emergency certificates usually are issued at a superintendents 
request and allow people to begin teaching fulltime while taking 
courses in traditional teacher education programs 
