<TEXT>
here is a look at the results of 
multiparty elections held in eastern european countries since 
democratic reforms began sweeping the region last year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
bulgaria the balkan country held its first free multiparty 
elections in 58 years on june 10 and 17 
the ruling socialist party which until april was the communist 
party clinched an absolute majority with 211 of parliaments 400 
seats 
the main opposition union of democratic forces a 16party 
alliance captured 144 seats the agrarian party a once docile 
ally of the communists won 16 seats and the rest went to small 
opposition groups and independents 
bulgaria is the first eastern european nation to freely elect a 
parliament dominated by the former communist party 
analysts say the socialists won because of bulgarias deep 
communist tradition which goes back nearly 100 years and fears 
that a rapid switch to private ownership as advocated by the 
opposition would cost jobs 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
czechoslovakia parliament elected former dissident playwright 
vaclav havel president dec 29 shortly after the nations peaceful 
revolution against communism 
the first free elections in 44 years were held june 89 for the 
300member parliament the movements that led the revolution 
havels civic forum and its sister group public against violence 
won 170 seats 
the communists finished a surprisingly strong second with 47 
seats and a threeparty christian democratic alliance won 40 seats 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
east germany the first free elections in east germanys 
41year history were held march 18 and an alliance of parties 
favoring quick unification with west germany won 192 of the 400 
seats in parliament 
local balloting on may 6 effectively gave communities control of 
their hometown governments and bureaucracies after four decades of 
centralized communist control the returns were similar to the 
march 18 results 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
hungary the first free elections in 43 years were held march 
25 and april 8 voters ended the communist era by giving the 
centerright hungarian democratic forum 165 of the 386 seats at 
