<TEXT>
leaders from 33 african countries many 
facing growing opposition at home gathered under tight security 
tuesday for a summit with french president francois mitterrand 
navy patrol boats 12 companies of riot police and more than 
1500 regular police officers were deployed in and around this posh 
beach resort as delegations arrived for the threeday summit 
french officials said 22 delegations would be led by a head of 
state two by prime ministers and nine by lesserranking cabinet 
ministers 
frenchafrican summits have been held every two years since the 
early 1960s this years gathering coincides with unprecedented 
political turbulence in frenchspeaking africa and unusually harsh 
domestic criticism of frances policies in its former colonies 
on tuesday prominent newspapers on the political right and left 
said france had persisted too long in supporting corrupt 
repressive african governments 
the french government speaks of democracy and continues to 
support dictatorial bloodstained regimes said lhumanite 
newspaper of frances communist party 
mitterrand in an interview with the prominent daily le monde 
accused other western countries of indifference toward africa and 
said france would never abandon the continent french aid money was 
subject to extremely rigorous review to ensure it was properly 
spent he said 
there have been antigovernment protests and demands for an end 
to oneparty rule in many african countries in recent months in 
several countries leaders have pledged to allow political 
pluralism 
