<DOCNO> AP900619-0121 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bridge builders east of the rockies must learn 
the lessons of last years deadly earthquake in california 
researchers said tuesday 
a major eastern earthquake will happen its just a question 
of when james cooper deputy chief structural engineer with the 
federal highway administration told about 250 bridge architects 
and state highway officials attending the international bridge 
conference in pittsburgh 
bridges are especially imperiled when built on soft soils and 
underlying hard rock a combination found in many eastern cities 
scientists say the condition amplifies tremors 
an earthquake is like an explosion sending energy in all 
directions us geological survey seismologist bob hamilton said 
in a telephone interview from reston va in the east the energy 
waves travel much further the crust is older and cooler less 
broken up by mountain building 
out west the mountain building is still going on the crust 
is busted up reducing the amplitude of an earthquake 
rocky ground covers most of the west exceptions are san 
francisco and oakland calif parts of which are built on soft 
ground known as bay mud 
the sections of the doubledecker interstate880 in oakland that 
collapsed during the oct 17 earthquake was built on bay mud 
klaus jacob a columbia university seismologist noted that 
other sections of the highway built on harder ground withstood the 
quake jacob said i880 was weakened by that extra jello pudding 
layer under the structure 
in the east major underground faults lie in the central 
mississippi river valley new england and south carolina 
the last major eastern quake in 1895 was centered near the 
junction of the ohio and mississippi rivers in charleston mo an 
1886 earthquake near charleston sc leveled most of the city and 
killed 20 people 
shock waves from an earthquake east of the rockies would travel 
30 to 40 times farther than waves from the same quake in 
california jacob said the us geological survey estimates more 
conservatively that such a quake would travel 20 times as far 
for example three thundering quakes in 181112 near the 
frontier settlement of new madrid mo were felt 850 miles away in 
washington dc 
we have the luxury in the east of having time between our 
earthquakes jacob said another new madrid earthquake may be 
around the corner tomorrow we should use the time we have to make 
repairs 
after the 1971 san fernando quake in california the state spent 
54 million to tie together sections of 1200 bridges with steel 
cables 
if a bridge isnt tied when it starts doing that wave it 
will bounce off its supports said james roberts chief bridge 
engineer for the california department of transportation 
california engineers also are experimenting with collaring 
bridge columns in steel which could have saved i880 said ian 
buckle deputy director of the national center for earthquake 
engineering research in buffalo ny 
buckle said state transportation officials should consider both 
methods when patching up aging bridges or building new ones 
the federal highway adminstration in its 1989 report to 
congress said 413 percent of the nations 577710 bridges were 
either structurally deficient or functionally obsolete 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

