<TEXT>
a towns ordinance requiring residents 
to obtain permits before installing political signs in their yards 
is unconstitutional a superior court judge ruled tuesday 
judge melanie famiglietti threw out the conviction of james 
lemoi who had been found guilty of erecting signs in his yard in 
1984 and 1985 without a permit 
lemoi 70 had been convicted in district court of violating 
barringtons ordinance and was fined 13000 he challenged his 
conviction and the american civil liberties union picked up his 
case 
barrington allows a variety of signs to be installed without a 
permit to advertise a house for sale a professional business such 
as a law firm in a home or signs tied to seasonal decorations 
other signs require a permit before they are erected 
lemoi installed signs in his yard twice the first was an appeal 
to the public for help after his wifes death and a fire at his 
house the judge said 
the second famiglietti said was a political statement about 
town officials 
under the barrington ordinance lemoi should have obtained a 
permit both times 
but the judge ruled that the town cannot regulate signs by their 
content 
if these very same signs indicated a doctors office in 
lemois home or were a theater marquee or were holiday 
decorations mr lemoi would not be in court today and would not be 
fined 13000 the judge said 
in december 1984 lemois wife died and just a few days later 
his house caught fire causing extensive damage he wasnt home at 
the time and was unhurt 
about 10 days after the fire lemoi put a sign up in his yard 
asking for help seven months later after he was unable to obtain 
police or fire department reports about the fire investigation he 
erected another sign stating simply come clean 
it was after that sign that barrington charged him in district 
court 
lemoi described famigliettis decision as swell 
he said he pursued the case for so long because he believed 
barrington was wrong 
i dont know why they treated me this way he said i was 
born and brought up in this town 
aclu lawyer elizabeth colt who represented lemoi said 
famigliettis decision came down squarely on the side of free 
speech guaranteed by the constitution 
you cant distinguish among signs ms colt said citing the 
prohibition on political signs its sign regulations got to be 
content neutral 
a lawyer for the town michael mosco said he would leave a 
decision whether to appeal the ruling to the town council but he 
defended ordinance saying it was reasonable 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

