<TEXT>
conservative supporters of a proposed 
constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget succeeded 
tuesday in their longrunning quest to bring the issue to the full 
house for a vote 
using a rarelysuccessful procedure supporters of the proposal 
overcame opposition by the houses democratic leadership and are 
now guaranteed a vote no later than next month 
they cant prevent this now said rep larry craig ridaho 
one of the measures sponsors 
supporters have long argued that an amendment requiring a 
balanced budget is the only way to eliminate the huge deficits of 
recent years which have been stuck in the 150 billion range 
opponents argue that such an amendment would not work because 
the real problem is the political stalemate over tax increases and 
spending cuts that might eliminate the budget gap 
for years democratic leaders have blocked balanced budget 
amendments from moving out of the house judiciary committee 
but under house procedures a measure can be taken away from a 
committee and brought to the full chamber for a vote if a majority 
of the 435 members sign a socalled discharge petition 
craig and his allies announced tuesday that they had collected 
their 218th signature the number needed 
the drive to round up those signatures recently had taken a 
controversial turn 
one supporter had threatened to release the names of cosponsors 
of the balancedbudget amendment who had refused to sign the 
petition but the supporter rep chuck douglas rnh said the 
matter was now moot 
constitutional amendments must be approved by twothirds votes 
of the house and senate and then ratified by at least 
threefourths of the states 
it is rare for discharge petitions to succeed 
since the houses current procedure was adopted in 1931 482 
such petitions have been filed according to richard beth of the 
congressional research service the research arm of congress 
just 43 of the petitions including tuesdays have succeeded 
in collecting enough signatures to force a house vote the last 
time one was successful was in 1986 when a vote was forced on a 
measure easing gun control laws 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

