recommend president bush veto landmark clean air legislation if the 
proposal contains a controversial jobs protection amendment when it 
reaches the white house 
i consider it bad environmental policy bad social policy and 
bad economic policy reilly said in discussing a provision that 
would assist workers who lose their jobs because of the tougher air 
pollution requirements 
both the senate and house are preparing for a conference 
committee to work out differences in largely similar bills to 
strengthen federal clean air laws for the first time in 13 years 
one of the differences involves an amendment in the house bill 
that would allow for 250 million to be spent in added unemployment 
compensation and retraining for workers if forced out of their jobs 
by the new legislation 
the administration says this could force industry spending well 
above the 21 billion or so annually called for by the senate 
version partly because it would be extremely difficult to tell if 
a job had been lost because of the provisions of the legislation 
reilly said his objections to this jobs proposal sponsored by 
rep bob wise dwva were strong enough that he would recommend 
that the president veto the entire bill if that section is not 
removed by the conference committee 
stressing that the administration is not insensitive to people 
losing their jobs reilly said that of the 17000 to 20000 jobs 
estimated to be lost by the tougher legislation only 4000 of 
those job losses would occur by 1995 
he said the major impact would not come until the next century 
giving society time to prepare through use of current job 
retraining programs 
the jobs issues is certain to be one of the main battles in the 
conference committee debate an aid package in the senate sponsored 
by sen robert byrd dwva lost by only one vote byrds 
amendment would have helped only coal miners while the less costly 
wise amendment expands the assistance to workers in all industries 
reilly briefing economics writers on the economic impacts of 
environmental legislation said the united states spends between 
80 billion to 90 billion annually on pollution control counting 
in both government enforcement efforts and cleanup costs borne by 
industry and consumers 
he said the administration projected that environmental 
spending which already amounts to 15 percent to 17 percent of 
the total us economy would rise to 25 percent of the gross 
national product by the year 2000 he said this figure would be 3 
percent if the costs of cleaning nuclear waste sites is included 
reilly said the administration understood the need to do all 
we can to protect the environment but to do it in a costeffective 
way 
