<TEXT>
conservatives objected tuesday to a supreme 
court ruling that directed a local tax increase to correct school 
segregation but some legal scholars told a senate panel the case 
didnt warrant a constitutional amendment to reverse it 
at issue is a 54 ruling in april that a federal judge could set 
aside state tax limitations and order local officials to raise 
taxes to correct a constitutional violation such as racial 
segregation in schools the case involved public schools in kansas 
city mo 
sen john danforth rmo has proposed a constitutional 
amendment to make clear that judges have no powers of taxation 
danforth and other amendment supporters argued that the court 
ruling was a straightforward example of the judiciary exercising a 
legislative function by directing a property tax increase in kansas 
city 
the decision is the predictable result of decades of relying 
ever more heavily on judicial power to solve social and political 
problems robert f nagel of the university of colorado school of 
law told the senate judiciary subcommittee on the constitution 
it is the predictable result of power going unchecked 
but nagel and other critics of the supreme court decision said 
that if an amendment is not approved legislation proposed by sens 
gordon humphrey rnh and strom thurmond rsc would suffice 
the measure would limit the remedial powers of federal judges by 
prohibiting orders requiring the federal government or any state 
or local government to impose any new tax or to increase any 
existing tax or tax rate 
conservative legal scholar bruce fein strongly criticized the 
danforth proposal for a constitutional amendment saying it would 
have a horrendous effect on simple justice by not 
permitting courts to correct constitutional wrongs in some cases 
i believe these proposals would foster arbitrary government 
throw a dagger at private and economic liberties and subvert the 
rule of law said fein 
fein said critics misinterpreted the decision saying it did 
not endow judges with imperial power to raise taxes to any 
level 
joining fein in opposition to a constitutional amendment was 
patricia a brannan a washington attorney for the kansas city 
school district she said the ruling followed a basic legal 
principle that judges must have the power to correct constitutional 
violations 
to do less would permit the political reluctance to raise 
taxes to deprive minorities of a remedy for demonstrated 
constitutional violations brannan said in a statement 
she pointed out that the supreme court held 90 in the kansas 
city case that a judge could not directly impose taxes the 
justices allowed the federal judge to block state laws that 
prevented the board from increasing taxes enough to pay the 
districts share of the desegregation plan 
missouri law requires voter approval before property taxes can 
be increased above a certain levy and in some instances a 
twothirds majority is necessary the locally elected school board 
she said now sets the actual levy within limits allowed by the 
courts 
the school board supported several tax increases but the voters 
rejected the proposals 
sen paul simon dill chairman of the senate panel said he 
remained undecided on the proposals but was reluctant to take the 
constitutional amendment approach 
