<TEXT>
federal safety investigators blamed both a 
railroad and a pipeline company tuesday for inadequate procedures 
in a may 1989 derailment and resulting pipeline explosion that 
killed six people in san bernardino calif 
the national transportation safety board said the calnev pipe 
line co gasoline pipeline was damaged by earthmoving equipment 
clearing the 69car southern pacific train that ran off the rails 
into several houses after speeding out of control down an incline 
four people were killed in the may 12 derailment and two in the 
petroleum pipeline explosion and fire nearly two weeks later 
the board said the probable cause of the train derailment was 
failure to determine the accurate weight for the train on that 
run failure to communicate to communicate to the engineer that 
fewer engines than he thought had working dynamic brakes and the 
inadequacy of southern pacific rules on allowable speed and brake 
operation down the incline 
dynamic braking is the running of the electric motors on the 
engine as generators and dissipating the electrical energy thus 
produced in a bank of resistors 
the ntsb blamed the pipeline accident on inadequate testing and 
inspection of the line following the derailment it said calnevs 
failure to inspect and test check valves on the 14inch pipe also 
contributed to the accident 
the fourmember board which investigates all major 
transportation and pipeline accidents issued 23 recommendations 
for federal and local action 
the independent board which held a hearing on the accident last 
year in san bernardino has no regulatory powers but its 
recommendations often lead to new procedures to improve safety 
the board advised southern pacific to require train dispatchers 
and train operators to improve communication on condition of the 
train the number of locomotives with functioning dynamic brakes 
the tonnage of the train and other items critical to safety 
investigators determined that only three of the six locomotives 
on the southern pacific train had functioning dynamic brakes while 
the engineer in the lead engine thought he had four 
the trains total weight was incorrectly estimated in southern 
pacifics computerized system at 6150 tons when it was actually 
9000 tons board staff investigators said and the railroads 
computers could still list the wrong weights for operating crews 
even after changes made by southern pacific following the accident 
based on actual tonnage available dynamic brakes and southern 
pacific operating rules the train should not have been permitted 
to operate down the 22 percent grade the board said in its 
conclusions 
the headend engineer may have been able to bring the train 
safely down the hill had he crested the hill at 15 mph which he 
would have been required to do if the dispatcher had informed him 
of the correct trailing tonnage 
it said the railroads operating rules provided inadequate 
guidance to the head engineer on the allowable speed and air 
brake settings down the grade 
it recommended that calnev test all mainline check valves 
annually 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

