<TEXT>
publisher roy mcdonald who turned a 
free weekly newspaper into one of tennessees most successful and 
distinctive papers died tuesday at age 88 
mcdonald founder and owner of the chattanooga newsfree press 
and the chattanooga publishing co died in his sleep at his home 
on nearby lookout mountain family members said 
known to friends family and the city as mr roy mcdonald 
had a reputation as both a hardnosed businessman and a generous 
boss who earned his employees loyalty 
the publisher who even in his 80s remained a daily fixture in 
the newsfree press newsroom worked in his office as usual monday 
the day before he died 
mcdonald was remembered for his circulation battles with the 
chattanooga times which ended in an antitrust settlement and a 
joint operating agreement with the other paper 
i knew him both as a formidable competitor and as a fair and 
collegial partner said ruth s holmberg publisher of the 
chattanooga times 
his wit and personal charm his strongly held views his 
faultless memory his fierce loyalty to family and friends his 
devotion to his craft all combined to create one of the most 
memorable persons in my life 
mcdonald who proudly called himself a merchant not a 
journalist started the free press in 1933 as an advertising 
circular delivered doortodoor at no charge 
in 1936 it became a daily paper with afternoon and sunday 
editions and three years later mcdonald bought the financially 
troubled chattanooga news to create the current paper 
the newsfree press has a conservative editorial policy and a 
style that includes a standard streamer headline on the front page 
and many photographs 
i always felt that running a picture was cheaper than setting 
type said mcdonald who routinely spent part of each afternoon 
laying out ads for the next days paper the only thing you were 
out was newsprint 
funeral services were set for friday 
survivors include his wife elizabeth mcdonald and five 
children frank mcdonald the newspapers president helen exum 
betsy anderson dr martha mcdonald of memphis and nancy reinke of 
arlington va 
</TEXT>
