the first ones that it justified doing it again said ray 
villard a spokesman for the space telescope science institute at 
johns hopkins university 
the hubble space telescope was launched into orbit april 25 
aboard the space shuttle discovery free from the distorting 
effects of earths atmosphere the 15 billion telescope is 
designed to study the furthest reaches of the universe 
five amateur astronomers were chosen from hundreds of 
applications the first time they have been allocated 17 hours of 
telescope time about 1 percent of the time granted to 
professionals villard said 
the number of applicants in the second group and the amount of 
time they will be given has not been decided he said 
i would expect it would be comparable villard said it 
might not sound like a lot but considering the competition there 
really is a lot of science that could be done with that much time 
the group of five astronomers chosen the first time will be 
allowed to use the hubble telescope in 1991 the next group will be 
given access in 1992 villard said 
its the opportunity of a lifetime not for professionals but 
for the average person said john hewitt one of the first five 
amateurs selected the program is very unique as far as i know 
no other observatory director has in a sense opened the door like 
this 
after a rigorous selection process the finalists are flown to 
baltimore to work with institute scientists and technicians to 
refine their observing requirements and are then scheduled along 
with professional programs the amateurs are invited back to the 
institute to observe the incoming data and use the institutes 
computers to analyze it 
frankly astronomy is one of the areas where an everyday 
