<TEXT>
ltv corp says it cannot afford to resume 
responsibility for 23 billion in pension liabilities despite a 
us supreme court decision upholding a government agencys effort 
to force the company to fund the plans 
ltv senior vice president julian scheer said the decision monday 
in favor of the pension benefit guaranty corp will delay the 
companys efforts to emerge from bankruptcy court protection 
ltv filed for chapter 11 protection four years ago because 
among other things we could not afford to make payments into these 
three pension plans the company said in a statement that 
situation has not changed we still cannot afford the plans it 
will be the companys objective to continue to seek a resolution 
which recognizes the fact 
ltv which has sold off much of its steel operations plans to 
reorganize as a streamlined company 
chriss street a bankruptcy expert at seidler amdec securities 
inc in chicago who has dealt with many of ltvs creditors said 
the company probably has enough cash to pay the claims but in 
paying the pension claim they would have to turn the keys to the 
company over to the pbgc and all the other creditors would 
essentially be left holding the bag 
the supreme court ruling assures that ltv will be mired in 
further litigation street said 
gary heinz an analyst at delaware bay co in new york said he 
would expect creditors to push the bankruptcy judge to end the 
companys exclusive right to come up with a reorganization plan 
by an 81 vote the supreme court said the pbgc acted within its 
authority when it ordered ltv and its subsidiary ltv steel co to 
restore the pension plans with unfunded liabilities of 23 billion 
labor secretary elizabeth dole who chairs the pbgcs board of 
directors said the ruling would help the agency protect the 
pensions of 40 million american workers and retirees 
while pensions as a whole are healthier than ever some 
companies in certain industries have seriously underfunded 
pensions mrs dole said pbgcs victory in this case will help 
discourage unwarranted termination of pension plans and encourage 
better funding of pensions 
after filing for bankruptcy reorganization in 1986 dallasbased 
ltv and its clevelandbased ltv steel subsidiary advised the pbgc 
that they could not fund their pension plans the plans were ended 
in 1987 
but in a later deal with the united steelworkers union ltv 
steel agreed to make up any benefits promised under the old plan 
but not covered by the federal pension insurance program 
the pbgc a government agency that takes over pension plans that 
end with insufficient money to fund benefits objected and ordered 
ltv to reassume responsibility for the pension plans mondays 
court ruling backed the agency 
were not happy with the decision but its certainly is not 
considered a backbreaker ltvs scheer said the question is 
how do we handle this tremendous obligation we dont have an 
answer 
retermination certainly is something well have to look at 
