<TEXT>
japans economy grew 5 percent in the past fiscal 
year boosted by brisk fourth quarter activity the economic 
planning agency announced tuesday 
it was the third straight year in which japans gross national 
product the countrys total output of goods and services expanded 
5 percent or more the government had forecast a 46 percent rate 
for the year 
in the fourth quarter which ended march 31 the agency said the 
gnp grew an inflationadjusted 25 percent for the first time in 
five years exports contributed slightly more to economic growth 
during the quarter than did domestic demand 
but increased domestic demand rather than exports accounted 
for most of the years economic expansion domestic demand 
contributed 57 percent to total growth compared to a negative 07 
percent for exports 
an agency official who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
the results showed that japans economic expansion now in its 43rd 
month continues to be led by domestic demand as japans economy 
shifts away from its past dependency on exports 
the official said the healthy growth rate in the januarymarch 
quarter showed that the sharp instability in japans stock and 
currency markets during the period had little impact on the economy 
from january through march japanese stock and bond prices 
plunged sharply and the yen weakened to 15765 yen to a dollar from 
14340 yen 
however personal consumption and private capital expenditures 
the main pillars of japans current economic expansion continued 
to grow although at a less rapid rate than during the previous two 
quarters 
gnp growth fluctuated sharply in fiscal 1989 and averaged 
slightly lower than the 53 percent registered in fiscal 1988 and 
the 54 percent in fiscal 1987 
analysts disagreed about the significance of the 85 percent 
surge in exports during the fourth quarter which overwhelmed a 21 
percent rise in imports 
the government official said temporary factors such as a sharp 
jump in auto exports to the united states in march to fill the 
unused portion of japans quota under its voluntary export 
restraint agreement were mainly responsible for the increase in the 
contribution of exports to growth 
toshiaki kakimoto chief economist with sumitomo bank said 
statistics from april should show a return to strong domestic 
demand the external sector should become negative again he 
said 
but kenneth courtis strategist and chief economist with 
deutsche bank in tokyo said temporary factors cannot explain all 
of the external sectors rebound from a negative 10 percent 
contribution in the octoberdecember quarter to a positive 13 
percent in the last quarter 
courtis said the yens weakness together with strong economic 
growth in asia and europe are more fundamental reasons behind the 
surge in exports 
now that japans markets have calmed down the japanese consumer 
is back on the street spending at a strong clip courtis said 
japans economic expansion has been running on two motors 
capital spending and consumer spending now exports are starting to 
kick into gear he said 
