<TEXT>
general motors corp plans to become the first 
major automaker to produce a fleet of natural gaspowered vehicles 
the houston chronicle reported tuesday 
a consortium of pipeline companies and producers will help pay 
for and purchase the 1000 light trucks the chronicle said 
the halfton trucks will be built at gms plant in troy mich 
and converted to natural gas by pas inc a detroitarea supplier 
the newspaper said 
quoting industry and state sources the newspaper said the 
announcement had been planned for wednesday but would come instead 
at julys economic summit in houston 
gm officials did not immediately return telephone calls this 
morning to the associated press the newspaper said gm would not 
comment 
this is a way to speed up gms research said vicki cho a 
spokeswoman for southern california gas co the nations largest 
gas distribution company we need to be involved in making this 
happen 
the chronicle said the consortium has agreed to provide as much 
as 1 million in funding for the final researching and testing of 
the vehicles 
the consortium also expected to purchase many of the gm trucks 
is composed of about 10 companies in texas california and 
colorado 
besides southern california gas it includes entex and enron 
corp of houston southern union gas co lone star gas co 
pacific gas and electric and san diego gas and electric 
executives representing the companies say the auto giant has 
reached a preliminary agreement to produce about 1000 natural 
gasburning trucks in 1991 
david polletta general manager of pas inc said the vehicles 
will be sold under the gm name and guaranteed by a gm warranty 
program 
industry officials say the gm move is the biggest boost yet for 
a natural gas vehicle movement that has been slow to materialize 
from the industrys standpoint this is something weve been 
trying to do for a long time said susan syler a spokeswoman for 
entex a houston natural gas distribution company we think that 
if we can get one of the big three out with these vehicles the 
others will follow 
