donald trump and his bank lenders reached a 
tentative agreement tuesday to restructure the 3 billion debt load 
the developer ran up in assembling his real estate empire a 
newspaper reported 
the new york times reported in an early edition of wednesdays 
paper that trumps four lead banks agreed to lend him 65 million 
and defer interest and principal payments on about 850 million of 
the developers nearly 2 billion in bank debt 
the agreement hinges on the four banks getting other lenders 
particularly japanese banks that are involved in loan syndicates 
for trump to agree to the deal the newspaper said the new loan 
package will be secured by nearly every asset in trumps real 
estate and gambling empire it said 
the times cited unidentified people involved in the talks 
the banks and trumps spokesman dan klores refused to comment 
on the status of the talks the four banks are citicorp 
manufacturers hanover corp chase manhattan corp and bankers 
trust co 
last week the parties reportedly were close to agreement on a 
plan under which trump would receive a 60 million loan that would 
enable him to keep making debt payments but over this past 
weekend the deal began falling apart as bankers argued over the 
contribution each would make and the collateral each would receive 
trump has yet to make a roughly 43 million payment due last 
friday on junk bonds used to finance the purchase of trump castle 
one of the developers three atlantic city hotelcasinos 
trump is in technical default on the bonds but is within a 
grace period during which he can still make the payment 
the developer also has not yet made a 30 million debt payment 
due manufacturers hanover corp 
trump has about 1 billion in junk bond debt outstanding in 
addition to roughly 2 billion in bank debt 
